<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06194043 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06194043 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  The Aluminum Company of America agreed Thursday to pay $7.5 million in fines-- including the largest criminal penalty ever levied for a hazardous wasteviolation -- for an array of state environmental offenses at its plant inMassena, N.Y. Among the violations admitted by the company was leavingPCB-contaminated soil piled on its property for more than 90 days in 1989, aviolation of state law. When the soil eventually was transported to a dump inAlabama, it was mislabeled as non-hazardous material. As part of a settlementnegotiated with New York, Alcoa officials pleaded guilty to misdemeanorcharges of improperly possessing, transporting, and disposing of hazardouswaste and of endangering the environment.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  $7.5 MILLION FINE FOR ALCOA POLLUTION  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Financial Digest  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910712  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  11D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  116  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday July 12, 199100194043,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>